review: I kept waiting for this book to really grab me but it never quite did. Whitehead's prose is incredible. I also think it was a brilliant concept to turI kept waiting for this book to really grab me but it never quite did. Whitehead's prose is incredible. I also think it was a brilliant concept to turn the metaphor of the Underground Railroad into a postmodern, steampunkish actual railroad. Something about the way characters and events were presented, however, left me feeling like things were happening slightly below the surface and Cora's story never felt very real for me. Perhaps this was an intentional device to make the tone of the book mirror the railroads. For me, though, it just left me feeling a bit disconnected and sleepy throughout the whole read. Still, this is a unique take on such an important subject and I'm glad I read it!...more

review: I had this book on my shelf for quite sometime. Every time I thought of reading it, this thought went through my head: "I don't feel like reading a b I had this book on my shelf for quite sometime. Every time I thought of reading it, this thought went through my head: "I don't feel like reading a book about a hermaphrodite right now." Then, when I finally started reading, I thought: "Well, this isn't really about a hermaphrodite as much as it is a family saga and a personal history." It wasn't until the end that I really got it. Callie/Cal isn't just a hermaphrodite, s/he is a person with a family and a history and a complex story to tell.  This book is beautifully written. It is dense and complicated and lovely to read. My only issue is that I found Callie/Cal's decision to live life as a male a bit abrupt but I think that was done intentionally to show that it actually wasn't an enormous, torturous decision for her/him but rather a natural one when the time was right.  In general, I would also say that the pacing felt a bit off. So much time spent in Turkey and such little time spent in NYC or Germany but again, I think it was all about the story that Callie/Cal was trying to tell which wasn't really about the gender decision but about her entire makeup, both genetic and narrative....more
